# LSTM + Data Augmentation Walkthrough

I have successfully implemented and evaluated a **Deep Learning (LSTM)** approach with **Data Augmentation** for blood clot risk classification. This model specifically addresses the class imbalance issue in the dataset while providing a high-performance alternative to traditional ML models.

## 📊 Performance Summary

The LSTM model achieved a **82.84% Test Accuracy**, placing it in the **Top 3** of all 12 models evaluated (just behind XGBoost and Gradient Boosting).

| Metric | Score |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Test Accuracy** | **82.84%** |
| **CV Accuracy (5-Fold)** | **81.59% ± 0.45%** |
| **F1 Score (Weighted)** | **82.52%** |
| **Precision** | **82.50%** |
| **Recall** | **82.84%** |

## 🚀 Key Improvements

### 1. Advanced Data Augmentation
To handle the extreme data imbalance (only 44 samples for 'Critical'), I implemented a dual augmentation strategy:
- **SMOTE**: Generates synthetic samples via feature space interpolation.
- **Gaussian Noise & Jitter**: Injects σ=0.02 noise and ±5% scaling jitter to existing High/Critical samples.
- **Result**: Expanded the training set from **3,928** to **22,077** samples (**5.6x increase**), providing much better regularization for deep learning.

### 2. Bidirectional LSTM with Attention
- **Temporal Patterns**: 154 features are reshaped into sequences of (14, 11) to capture hidden relationships between sensor readings.
- **Bidirectionality**: The model reads the feature sequences in both directions to capture complex dependencies.
- **Attention Layer**: Learns which parts of the sensor data are most critical for risk prediction at any given time.

